Project Context & Prime Directive
You are tasked with building a Personal Financial Management (PFM) module for the Qualia DB ecosystem. This is a strictly localized, offline-first architecture designed to maximize user agency over their financial data.
CRITICAL CONSTRAINT: Under no circumstances is the system permitted to route user data, receipt images, or ledger entries to third-party cloud APIs (e.g., Google Cloud Vision, OpenAI API, AWS Textract) for processing. All data extraction, specifically Optical Character Recognition (OCR) and semantic parsing, must occur on the user's local hardware or designated edge node.

Phase 1: Local Ingestion & Edge Extraction Pipeline
Objective: Ingest raw receipt images and extract structured semantic data locally.

Ingestion Interface: Build a lightweight interface for camera capture or file upload (PDF/JPG/PNG).

Local Processing Engine: Implement an integration with a local inference engine (target compatibility with local runners like LM Studio or Ollama).

Vision-Language Model (VLM) Task: Configure a small, efficient local VLM (e.g., a quantized Qwen-VL or Moondream) to process the ingested image.

Extraction Target (JSON): The local model must return a strictly formatted JSON object containing:

vendor_name (String)

transaction_date (ISO-8601)

total_amount (Float)

tax_amount (Float)

line_items (Array of objects, optional fallback)

Storage: Store the original image locally within the DB's file structure and link its URI to the resulting ledger entry.

Phase 2: Spatial-Economic Ontology (Data Schema)
Objective: Map financial transactions to physical movements and specific assets to support automated apportionment for mobile environments or field research.

Entity Mapping: Design the database schema to handle the following relationships:

Transaction: The core ledger entry.

Spatial_Log: GPS coordinates, polyline routes, or location tags at the time of transaction.

Asset: The physical entity associated with the cost (e.g., a specific vehicle, hardware, or property).

Apportionment Logic: Create a calculation utility that queries the Spatial_Log and Transaction tables to determine the percentage of asset usage (e.g., fuel) dedicated to specific contexts (e.g., 60% field research / 40% personal).

Phase 3: The Tax Rules Abstraction Layer
Objective: Isolate geographically volatile tax legislation from the immutable database core.

Schema Engine: Build a processing engine that accepts external, hot-swappable JSON or YAML "Tax Rule Schemas."

Rule Definitions: These external schemas will define regional tax brackets, deductible categories, and depreciation rates.

Processing: The engine applies the active Tax Rule Schema to the core ledger to generate tax estimates and categorize expenses, ensuring the user only needs to update the schema file when legislation changes, leaving the DB architecture untouched.

Phase 4: Verifiable Export & Accountant Handoff
Objective: Generate standardized, highly trusted outputs for legacy accounting ecosystems.

Standardized Exporters: Implement parsers to generate .OFX, .QIF, and formatted .CSV files from the ledger queries.

Cryptographic Provenance: Include a cryptographic hash of the original scanned receipt in the export metadata.

Audit Package Generation: Create a utility that bundles the standardized export file with a local directory of the associated receipt images, creating a clean, verifiable zip archive to hand over to an accountant.

